rb types (unaccusatives, unergatives, (di)transitives, psych verbs), morpho-syntactic operations (prefixation, simple vs. particle verbs), case distinctions (dative vs. accusative, case vs. prepositions), argument and voice alternations (dative vs. benefactive alternation, active vs. passive), word order alternations and the impact of animacy, agentivity, and eventivity on argument structure. The volume will be of interest to theoretical linguists, psycholinguists, and corpus linguists interested in the syntax of argument structure and its modelling using precise empirical methods.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aArgumentstruktur. 4aDiathese. 4aKasus. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Syntax.2bisacsh  aArgument Alternations.  aArrgument Structure.  aVoice, Case.1 aAlexiadou, Artemis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexiadou, Artemis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBaumann, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandt, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCzypionka, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarby, Jeannique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEulitz, Carsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoop, Helen de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrwin, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPappert, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPechmann, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchumacher, Petra B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpathas, Giorgos, eco